comment_text_display: Do they last like Samsung TVs do?
comment_text_original: Do they last like Samsung TVs do?

comment_text_display:
@@345power no one knows how much a tv could last. After working in electronics store, I realized 2 things:
-There is no brand that we can confidently claim it is long lasting
-All top brands, in the past 5 years, have dropped the quality, especially in the low budget area.

We get daily, different TVs that we send to the service for repairs, some benefiting from the extended warranty, some still covered by the warranty from manufacturer.

My dad had an LG TV from 2015 till 2018, The panel got degraded pretty fast, probably because he used to leave the TV ON 24/7 on Vivid. Now he has a Samsung UHD TV since 2018, it still works, even if the software got a little sluggish, with slightly degraded panel, usually it is easy to spot some black spots while watching football or the background is a lighter color.

In my room I got an LG UHD TV that I use mainly for some casual gaming and for some movies. I got it in 2022, it still works like it should. I also have a 32" Samsung TV (bought in 2016) that I use mostly as a secondary monitor for PC, and from time to time for watching some football, while I am at PC. I only had it once in the service for a motherboard replacement (in 2017). Now the panel is degraded with intense bleeding on the left side of the screen, and software basically unusable, as it became too slow to even use the smart hub. At least the colors are still ok after a little tweaking.

My brother got a Hisense TV (58A7H) in his living room, he bought it in 2022 and it still works as it should. And he also uses a 32" LG HD TV as a secondary monitor for his PC. I bought that TV for him in 2018, it still works as it should, without feeling sluggish, with no perceptible panel degradation.

At the end of the day, all I can say, get whatever you like, and if you can go to a store to test them, it would be even better.

comment_text_display: I have a 75 u8000f. I will say the backlight bleeding can be terrible at times if you are viewing something in dark mode with a white image or white text. so bad that it's not even fading smoothly. Like it will look like squares within squares.(white, grey, black) Upscaling content from 1080p looks very blurry. Maybe only on the larger tv's. Is this a thing on the 55? And lastly my personal biggest flaw is the 2 rear facing hdmi inputs. I have my tv mounted and when i tried to hook up 2 things at once it would keep the tv from being able to go on the mount as the hdmi cable would be either hitting the wall or mount depending on your bracket size. I did get a 90 degree hdmi adapter which fixed the issue but for anyone thinking of getting one of these keep that in mind.

comment_text_display:
In this case, it’s a limitation of the tech. MicroLED is a breakthrough but it’s still hard to get them small enough and close enough to get smaller size displays. 115” not only hits a segment that wants bigger screens and cutting edge tech, but it conveniently allows them to ship something at the threshold of density they can hit.

Over time, as the tech matures, we will get smaller sizes. Ironically, smaller tech typically costs more initially because it requires the condensing of a lot of tech. Think of how computers used to take up an entire room and now you have one in your pocket.

comment_text_display: It's an issue with both the SoC in the TV and Samsung's software. The SoC is bad because they can get away with it, and the software is typical of Samsung, way tooover-bloatedd. It is the same with their phones (mostly cheaper ones, but 3-year-old flagships struggle more than competitors too), there is no reason a 200$ phone needs 20GB+ of OS files and 15 services they need to connect to from the start. The TV would also probably run well if they just removed the 20 different ad-services they have on it by default.

comment_text_display:
to be clear the wifi connection isn't on 6, that's a backhaul/device comm channel, which is... normal-ish? for wifi 7 equipment when leadership/marketing drives instead of engineers. the... thinking... there is that since literally everything used in home construction (even non insulated interior walls with a half-inch sheet of drywall on either side) blocks 6ghz at consumer broadcast strengths the interference inside of a room will be pretty limited

there are a lot of real world problems with this series of assumptions but it's not quite insanity. it's really easy to get pretty quiet on 6ghz even in an apartment building.

comment_text_display: As an owner of 3 Frame TVs (Non-Pro's from 2020 and 2022) due to the desire of "TVs that don't look like TVs". Everything Quinn said in this is true. Can't relate to the wireless portion since the Non-Pros use a cable to connect the box to the TV, but the Samsung software is atrocious, and is still not fixed. The "art mode" is NEVER consistent in turning on or off correctly after turning off connected devices. Software is dog-slow and Samsung is adamant on trying to make sure you pay for their art subscription for features that should be STANDARD on a TV focused on letting you display art at a premium price tag. The mounting method changed in 2022 I think? the original mount was at least long enough to get one screw onto a stud, but the new mount sucks. If I were to say anything positive, it's that it can be confused for art sometimes, and it definitely makes a room feel a little nicer. Idk if I'd ever pay for the "Pro" version though. The regular frames were already too expensive for what they are, and I feel like we'd all less harsh on these TVs if the price matched the frustration but it doesn't.

Software is dog-slow and Samsung is adamant on trying to make sure you pay for their art subscription for features that should be STANDARD on a TV focused on letting you display art at a premium price tag. The mounting method changed in 2022 I think? the original mount was at least long enough to get one screw onto a stud, but the new mount sucks. If I were to say anything positive, it's that it can be confused for art sometimes, and it definitely makes a room feel a little nicer. Idk if I'd ever pay for the "Pro" version though. The regular frames were already too expensive for what they are, and I feel like we'd all less harsh on these TVs if the price matched the frustration but it doesn't.

comment_text_display:
I install these TV's. Samsung Frame TV's are absolute garbage and that's saying something because Samsung's entire TV lineup is already pretty shitty to begin with. They have uneven backlighting, a lot of their lower mid-level TV's using edge lighting instead of backlighting or even local dimming. I don't know how samsung has managed to be the #1 TV seller in the US for as long as they have.

Oh and CEC is so fucking bad that even AVR's can't properly communicate with the Frame, let alone the Frame Pro. Had a diag today for a Frame going to Art Mode and then the receiver not coming back on when exiting Art Mode. You had to cycle the AVR manually and then ARC wouldn't work until you either restarted the TV/Toggled ARC/disconnected the HDMI and plugged it back in. I tell anyone that buys these to return them and get an LG or a Sony or to get a TCL and get the same shitty image but at a more palatable price.

comment_text_display:
I'm beyond impressed, that you got this thing to connect to your Unifi Wireless.
A friend of mine bought one and it hates the Ui wireless so much it only connects to a separate SSID locked to 2.4Ghz Wifi4 (Unifi calls this enhanced IoT compatibility mode). If I have that SSID broadcasting on multiple APs, it chooses the one with the worst signal. Had to restrict it to the AP in the same room to get it to behave.
Insane that the company that builds phones that support Wifi7 MLO cannot get a TV to connect at all to a standard WPA2/3 mixed ssid.
comment_text_original:
I'm beyond impressed, that you got this thing to connect to your Unifi Wireless.
A friend of mine bought one and it hates the Ui wireless so much it only connects to a separate SSID locked to 2.4Ghz Wifi4 (Unifi calls this enhanced IoT compatibility mode). If I have that SSID broadcasting on multiple APs, it chooses the one with the worst signal. Had to restrict it to the AP in the same room to get it to behave.
Insane that the company that builds phones that support Wifi7 MLO cannot get a TV to connect at all to a standard WPA2/3 mixed ssid.

comment_text_display:
set it to 0 or 1 and play with whatever your specific samsung tv's upscaling features are; tbf this is a big pet peeve of mine (for almost all video devices/sources you can only set these things to "auto" or one specific setting for an input, and there's unlikely to be any changes there because power users are such a tiny fraction of the market and regular consumers just aren't going to care). once you have motion smoothing etc turned off or at least tuned you will probably have a much better experience.

also check your input, if you've got a separate digital source like many types of cable box you probably have an entire separate menu that might need to be tweaked

unnnnnfortunately the settings you're going to want for most movies (absolutely cranked resolution and whatever gets you good blacks, and the lowest framerate you can comfortably get) are basically the opposite of what you'll want on sports content (decent resolution, strong contrast and saturation, and the highest framerate your monitor supports)

comment_text_display: @@noneuklid First of all, I watched this on a hardwired desktop computer. And second, YouTube (and most on-demand streaming services) buffers video; television and video game consoles are not buffered.
comment_text_original: @@noneuklid First of all, I watched this on a hardwired desktop computer. And second, YouTube (and most on-demand streaming services) buffers video; television and video game consoles are not buffered.

comment_text_display:
@@Yay295 the use case for TVs in the 2020s is generally for streaming digital content. even traditional cable providers are moving towards primarily streamed content with things like the Verizon Stream box being basically a worse AppleTV that streams Verizon's cable TV service.

video games aren't buffered but they also don't particularly need or benefit from complex audio and are a special case for video. If you watch a high-stakes pro tournament in some FPS or arena game, you'll notice that few or likely none of the players are wearing wired headsets. PCM, even five-channel PCM, is comfortably under the bandwidth limits on BLE or other 2.4ghz connections ("DVD-quality" surround audio is something like 4-6 megabits/second vs BLE's max of 24).

4k/120hz can be pretty demanding, it's a couple orders of magnitude more data -- but again, people game over wifi all the time. There are a bunch of 'tricks' for how this works (the PC renders video from compressed data, not from raw) but they aren't strictly needed in the era of multi-band 5ghz+6ghz equipment. Which is good, as the Frame Pro can't benefit from most of them since the video processing is nearly all done in the OneConnect box. I don't actually know the protocol the box and TV use, just that it's loosely based on AXE/BE wifi standards. BE has a per-link theoretical limit of about the same as an older HDMI cord and I expect that the OC/monitor connection has both multiple wireless connections and some form of compression.

Does that always work? Obviously not, for Samsung. But that's because their ability to coordinate multiple engineering solutions is shit for their TVs, not because the thing they're trying to do is some distant impossibility. The era of "good wireless A/V is impossible" ended years ago. Most people do live wireless 1080p/"dvd" audio without complaint on devices every day, and more demanding stuff is absolutely possible with the right solutions.

comment_text_display:
@@iloveband10000 do you get call backs on fire tvs

because the low end versions of those will do nuisance prompts until you connect them to the internet

you can set it up to go straight to input from power on BUT if it's not connected the user will get nuisance prompts, and if it is connected the user will also get nuisance prompts for updates and even advertising until you disable every single one (and then they get switched back on after an update)

comment_text_display:
​@@wellivea1 depending on the mfr and OS generation "store mode" is what you're looking for, although that will sometimes intentionally disable features that realistically do not actually require the nuisance/adware/etc services; they do it to stop home consumers from just using store mode (and say it's for 'security')

commercial displays also (usually) have no meaningful user-facing OS, but are more expensive and can require some specialized knowledge or even equipment to configure

comment_text_display: I never understood why anyone would opt for this wireless option instead of the wire. The single wire of the normal frame is so much easier to hide or route through a wall than running a power line there. When I got my first Frame (I have two), I also got a matching sound bar and it never worked properly. When it was connected, it worked great but when you turn the TV on, the matching sound bar wouldn't turn on and you'd instead have to change the output to the sound bar every time. In the end we just got some HomePod Minis and run everything through an AppleTV instead. If only it would activate art mode using the power off signal from said AppleTV though. These (wired) TVs make amazing bedroom televisions but I question the sanity of anyone trying to use one as a main lounge TV or something to game on.

comment_text_display:
Now I know absolutely nothing about this TV but lets be clear here about TFT displays. They got white light LEDs in the back. Not blue ones. This white light then goes through a layer of liquid crystal which is where the name LCD comes from. That layer can very accurately block or dim light from behind the RGB sub pixels. But it cant block 100% of the light. Thats why black looks washed out on regular LCDs. How that layer of liquid crystal blocks/dims the light defines which type of panel you got. We know those as TN, VA or the most common one these days IPS.
Now what I assume micro rgb does in this TV is that it skips any of that and uses basically only the backlighting. But instead of white its RGB coloured. Conventional LEDs for the longest time couldnt actually be build small enough to just do that in the form factors required. Thats where oled came in. It has a bunch of drawbacks but those organic leds could be made small enough to just be the subpixels themselves. Well something like that.

comment_text_display:
Okay, so what you're saying is this:
About 20 years ago when Mega-Electronic Companies, started phasing out the Cathode-Ray Tube TVs. Remember those big monitors. If you find one, put it's screen under a magnifying glass, simple one. Every strip is made of hundreds of sections laid out in a vertical line. So each of these sections is further divided into RGB(The Red Green Blue Dot) yes, that was the original RGB Dot.
After all this talk of going digital, the technique for constructing new technology remains the same as the one invented, what 70-75 years ago? We don't have anything new. If the technique is old, then I'll bet anything, that it's a old age pig with a modern lipstick, what I don't get is why they're charging 30,000 dollars for something that isn't even a newer concept. World had colored television since the 70s.
This concept of RGB Dot has been around since the time colour televisions were in existence.
